1
00:00:01,330 --> 00:00:27,000
Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhutasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhutasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhutasa

2
00:00:27,199 --> 00:00:31,626
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,109 --> 00:00:47,588
So it's just an opportunity to just revise the principles of meditation and go over the problems that we come across in terms of dealing with certain mental states.

4
00:00:54,165 --> 00:01:08,001
One of the core words of the Buddhist teachings is this word dukkha, which translates as a hard place.

5
00:01:10,984 --> 00:01:12,807
So we're in a hard place.

6
00:01:13,706 --> 00:01:21,456
And the idea is that if we get it right, it'll become sukha, it'll be a happy place, an easy place.

7
00:01:24,709 --> 00:01:48,216
And the process whereby we bring that about is a dual process, both of allowing old conditionings based on wrong understandings to exhaust themselves and developing new conditionings.

8
00:01:48,477 --> 00:01:54,243
So from an ordinary relative phenomenal point of view, the Buddha

9
00:01:54,933 --> 00:02:03,664
you know Siddhartha Gautama when he was fully self-enlightened he was still the personality the character etc.

10
00:02:03,703 --> 00:02:21,227
was still conditioned conditioned by the situation he found himself in but according to him he was always happy happy or calm equanimous the world argues with me I don't argue with the world

11
00:02:24,801 --> 00:02:49,205
now if we investigate how we create these conditionings then hopefully we can sort of go back on that process one of the things we do isn't it is to use our intellect and our imagination

12
00:02:50,401 --> 00:03:17,622
to create within ourselves and to develop within ourselves a particular conditioning so if for instance we have already a disposition within us which is anxious then through our thoughts and through our imaginings we'll create an anxious world around us we'll worry worry about this, worry about that

13
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:43,205
and with all these things there's a presumption that the more you worry the less you'll have to worry about but the opposite tends to be true the more you worry the more you worry and then you suddenly then you sort of begin to wake up that real that you and you begin to perhaps ask the question well am i the one who's creating the worry

14
00:03:47,640 --> 00:04:17,326
if you have a disposition which is depressive always looking at the negative side of things so we tend to find more and more things to be depressed about and there's a sort of relief in that because you're always proving yourself right

15
00:04:19,298 --> 00:04:20,620
I am depressed.

16
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:22,822
The world is depressing me.

17
00:04:23,442 --> 00:04:25,305
Everywhere I look, it is depressing.

18
00:04:28,250 --> 00:04:35,117
And what we get ourselves into, isn't it, is sort of a lock situation where you don't see the end of that spiral.

19
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:38,403
You try to break out of it.

20
00:04:38,442 --> 00:04:40,846
You try to buy some ice cream or something.

21
00:04:42,867 --> 00:04:45,170
But then you worry whether the ice cream is doing you any good.

22
00:04:47,254 --> 00:04:48,815
And you get depressed about it.

23
00:04:50,432 --> 00:04:59,064
So, when we realize that it's thought which is actually creating the world for us.

24
00:04:59,084 --> 00:04:59,565
Thought.

25
00:05:02,610 --> 00:05:04,012
Thought and imaginings.

26
00:05:06,214 --> 00:05:06,375
Yeah?

27
00:05:06,935 --> 00:05:12,384
Information comes in and we play with it inside the mind, as it were.

28
00:05:14,867 --> 00:05:18,853
And we play with it from a particular disposition, of a particular...

29
00:05:18,985 --> 00:05:48,958
position that we've taken in life and then we project it we deposit it on the world and the world funnily enough mirrors it back to us so if you go around feeling depressed looking depressed everybody else around you gets depressed and if they don't want to get depressed they don't want to see you so you end up getting more depressed because now the world is truly depressing

30
00:05:55,620 --> 00:06:15,290
Now, all the Buddha is saying is, if you stop for a minute and try to take a position within ourselves to observe the mind, to observe what it's actually doing, then we'll come very quickly to understand that all we have to do is stop this form of indulgence.

31
00:06:16,490 --> 00:06:20,396
And that's really, you know, the training of the vipassanā.

32
00:06:21,540 --> 00:06:34,860
So we're discovering a place in ourselves, rediscovering a place in ourselves, and constantly trying to re-establish it, a place where we can observe what's going on.

33
00:06:38,285 --> 00:06:42,951
And we start with placing the attention on the body itself, because that's the most obvious.

34
00:06:43,052 --> 00:06:49,000
You can sense the body, you can feel the body, it's not that difficult to get in contact with it.

35
00:06:50,110 --> 00:07:17,485
and one of the main reasons for doing that is to try and release this intelligence try to sort of draw it out of its confusion with thought that's the first thing you see this intelligence we have, this intuitive intelligence

36
00:07:19,490 --> 00:07:31,382
generally speaking defines itself as thought, as imagining, I think therefore I am, that sort of statement.

37
00:07:33,704 --> 00:07:46,677
But when we take this position in ourselves of the observer, of this observation post, we can actually see the images in the mind, they can become very clear to us.

38
00:07:47,906 --> 00:08:17,778
thoughts are often too quick for us and we wake up after a sequence of thoughts and then reflect on it as some form of thinking or worrying or whatever but in some good states of concentration when the mind is really steady when this attention is really clarified you might even see a thought passing in front of you like a neon sign and these sorts of experiences

39
00:08:18,264 --> 00:08:47,529
are telling us that there is something as it were prior to or beyond the thinking process when we go into emotions normally or often we find ourselves hijacked by a particular mental state suddenly you're angry suddenly you're anxious, whatever but when you actually sit like this and find that observation post when a mental state arises

40
00:08:47,644 --> 00:08:51,110
you can, as it were, feel it as an object.

41
00:08:52,030 --> 00:08:58,778
You can investigate it as if it were something you had in your hands, a piece of putty, a dough.

42
00:09:01,163 --> 00:09:09,452
You can actually begin to investigate the feelings, the sensations that we would normally call anger or depression or anxiety.

43
00:09:12,778 --> 00:09:16,081
So you're becoming intimate with your psychic life.

44
00:09:17,850 --> 00:09:19,793
in a way that you wouldn't normally be.

45
00:09:20,475 --> 00:09:28,106
Normally, the ordinary person wouldn't make a distinction between that knowing and what they're experiencing.

46
00:09:28,246 --> 00:09:35,097
They are what they feel, they are what they're experiencing, they are their thoughts, they are the body.

47
00:09:35,118 --> 00:09:37,981
If the body hurts, it's me, it's me that's hurting.

48
00:09:41,246 --> 00:09:46,254
But here, by taking that observation post, when we find pain in the body,

49
00:09:46,403 --> 00:09:51,349
discomfort in the knee, whatever, it becomes an object.

50
00:09:51,929 --> 00:09:53,731
We've distanced ourselves from it.

51
00:09:55,293 --> 00:09:57,176
That's our first position, as it were.

52
00:09:58,717 --> 00:10:11,313
As soon as you do that, as soon as we make any of this stuff an object, whether it's the thoughts or imaginings, emotions, feelings, sensations, we've created a very different relationship to it.

53
00:10:14,601 --> 00:10:38,279
before I would have said my knee hurts but when I'm sitting in meditation here like this and the pain comes and I say pain is there it's not mine there's a sort of break in my relationship with it and I can begin to see it as just sensation

54
00:10:40,942 --> 00:10:52,922
When I can begin to distance myself from these things like this, I become aware of this other relationship that I've had, which at the moment I'm not indulging.

55
00:10:53,982 --> 00:10:56,807
And here we're coming to this second noble truth.

56
00:10:56,827 --> 00:11:03,238
So the first one is that there is this unsatisfactoriness, the suffering that we've created.

57
00:11:03,352 --> 00:11:32,297
and the second one is the role of desire now I have to be careful with this English word desire because it's not quite doesn't hit the nail on the head it's really a relationship we have with the world where we're constantly trying to be happy with it we're constantly trying to find a way of being in the world which makes us happy so that this happiness is dependent on the world when I say the world here I mean on what we experience

58
00:11:32,277 --> 00:11:33,097
what we experience.

59
00:11:33,158 --> 00:11:36,341
So, how does that manifest within us?

60
00:11:36,662 --> 00:11:53,863
Well, whenever I get something pleasant, a pleasant feeling in the body, say a nice joy comes up or a calmness, I immediately want to disappear into it, absorb into it, I may want to indulge it, I want to maintain it there.

61
00:11:53,842 --> 00:12:04,518
Sometimes we're sitting here and finally we can say we've got some sort of steady attention and we feel that we're calm and peaceful and we're really watching.

62
00:12:05,139 --> 00:12:10,466
And then somebody comes in and bangs the door off, sneezes into the back of our necks, you see.

63
00:12:10,485 --> 00:12:11,947
And all hell's let loose inside.

64
00:12:12,428 --> 00:12:15,413
You want to kill somebody.

65
00:12:15,847 --> 00:12:26,299
And what that shows us is that we've entered into this beautiful space and unwittingly we've tried to hold it, we've tried to contain it, we've tried to not let it move.

66
00:12:28,001 --> 00:12:32,847
And in that way, whether we like it or not, we find ourselves in conflict with the world.

67
00:12:33,749 --> 00:12:38,514
So when somebody sneezes, you know, we feel irritated by it.

68
00:12:40,063 --> 00:12:48,456
But if we were in that easy state of open awareness, you see, there would just be the sneeze and the sneeze would disappear.

69
00:12:49,578 --> 00:12:51,982
It would just be like a bird flying across your sight.

70
00:12:56,710 --> 00:12:58,913
Just one thing happening after another.

71
00:12:59,956 --> 00:13:03,961
Now, when we are...

72
00:13:04,735 --> 00:13:12,962
Maintaining that, we'll also see that whenever something unpleasant arises, there's always this resistance to it.

73
00:13:13,583 --> 00:13:15,365
You just don't want that.

74
00:13:16,927 --> 00:13:30,220
And that resistance is a relationship of wanting to get rid of, destroy, annihilate anything which I am experiencing as undermining my comfort, undermining my particular state.

75
00:13:32,596 --> 00:13:35,763
So again I find myself in conflict.

76
00:13:35,783 --> 00:13:37,427
I'm always in conflict with what's happening.

77
00:13:38,548 --> 00:13:51,177
Either I'm trying to hold on to something and stop something entering into that experience because this is the way I want to be or I'm trying to get rid of something which I find upsetting.

78
00:13:54,347 --> 00:14:14,787
exhausting in it and if of course this pain or whatever that comes up begins to you know get a bit too much for me then the anxiety comes the fear comes so those are your those are our three basic positions in the world

79
00:14:16,268 --> 00:14:31,570
we're either holding on to something, we're either being greedy, we're either trying to maintain a particular situation, or we're trying to get rid of it.

80
00:14:32,932 --> 00:14:34,474
We're trying to get rid of a situation.

81
00:14:34,913 --> 00:14:37,498
And if that situation is too much for us, we run for it.

82
00:14:42,004 --> 00:14:42,445
That's it.

83
00:14:44,062 --> 00:14:55,599
If we observe ourselves, even if you're just sitting watching a TV, if you watch yourself, you're constantly shifting your position, moving around the armchair.

84
00:14:56,559 --> 00:15:01,868
You just can't maintain any place which is slightly uncomfortable.

85
00:15:05,880 --> 00:15:14,831
Now that wouldn't be so bad in itself, I suppose, were it not that it was based on a wrong understanding as to where we're going to find happiness.

86
00:15:16,173 --> 00:15:22,780
I mean, if happiness could be found by playing this wanting-not-wanting game, then we ought to keep playing it.

87
00:15:23,741 --> 00:15:25,124
Because, well, we want to be happy.

88
00:15:26,044 --> 00:15:26,546
Very simple.

89
00:15:27,907 --> 00:15:34,335
But it's when we realize it's not going to deliver that, and we look at our fundamental position,

90
00:15:35,480 --> 00:15:48,423
You see, there's an unspoken presumption that happiness is based upon the sensual world.

91
00:15:48,605 --> 00:15:57,201
In other words, I've got to find happiness within this mortal frame, within this body, within this mind.

92
00:16:00,471 --> 00:16:05,278
And all the time, the messages I'm getting from the world is, it's not possible.

93
00:16:06,561 --> 00:16:09,946
And it's not possible because things are changing anyway.

94
00:16:10,186 --> 00:16:11,928
I can't maintain anything.

95
00:16:11,969 --> 00:16:16,816
As soon as I try to hold on to something, I just find that it slips out of my grasp.

96
00:16:16,855 --> 00:16:21,062
It's like holding water.

97
00:16:21,081 --> 00:16:24,167
And then I find I've not got that much control.

98
00:16:24,332 --> 00:16:31,183
So to define myself, to define a self, surely it's about, if this is me, I should be able to control it.

99
00:16:31,703 --> 00:16:37,913
If this is my body, if this is me, if my body is me, then I should be able to do what I want with it.

100
00:16:37,933 --> 00:16:42,640
I should be able to make it grow a bit more.

101
00:16:42,682 --> 00:16:45,947
Hopefully.

102
00:16:47,389 --> 00:16:50,052
I should be able to eat as much as I want and not grow fat.

103
00:16:52,327 --> 00:16:54,330
I should be able to do whatever I want with it, but I can't.

104
00:16:54,509 --> 00:17:00,616
I find myself in a peculiar situation of being in a body over which I've got minimal control.

105
00:17:01,216 --> 00:17:03,299
I mean, I can wave my arms about and all that.

106
00:17:07,003 --> 00:17:08,204
I can't stop it aging.

107
00:17:10,487 --> 00:17:11,709
I can't stop it dropping dead.

108
00:17:12,449 --> 00:17:13,450
That's the important thing, isn't it?

109
00:17:15,633 --> 00:17:17,694
I don't mind the aging bit, I just don't want to drop dead.

110
00:17:20,864 --> 00:17:24,248
I don't mind, I don't mind the body as it is, it's great, I just don't want it to fall ill.

111
00:17:28,732 --> 00:17:41,727
So here we have, you know, we're in this sort of peculiar state where there's a drive within us to be happy in the world and the world just isn't playing ball.

112
00:17:42,548 --> 00:17:47,614
It's just not coming, it's just not, it's not responding in a way that it ought to really.

113
00:17:50,362 --> 00:17:59,337
So maybe I've got it wrong, you see, and this is the Buddha, remember, the Buddha's own life story mirrors this same path.

114
00:17:59,357 --> 00:18:07,531
The Buddha isn't just simply the exemplar, you know, the one who actually sets an example.

115
00:18:07,692 --> 00:18:08,534
He's the archetype.

116
00:18:09,094 --> 00:18:14,022
All of us have to follow this particular path if we want to find this liberation.

117
00:18:15,589 --> 00:18:40,280
and what we begin with through this meditation is this process of renunciation now renunciation is not you know self-mortification we're not trying to make ourselves suffer there's no point in that at all and this is also something that the Buddha discovered wasn't it he went through a period of self-mortification

118
00:18:41,407 --> 00:18:49,656
And he ended up by saying it was just suffering, more suffering, unprofitable, and well, ignoble really, sort of beating yourself up.

119
00:18:53,842 --> 00:19:02,131
So whatever renunciation is, it's not a case of putting ourselves into painful situations just for the sake of it.

120
00:19:03,653 --> 00:19:10,420
Renunciation is that process of beginning to let go of those things that we find ourselves attached to.

121
00:19:11,580 --> 00:19:19,272
those things that we are depending on for happiness, because we begin to realize that that isn't true happiness.

122
00:19:21,056 --> 00:19:28,107
Any happiness which is dependent on something is fragile.

123
00:19:29,450 --> 00:19:37,082
You know, if my happiness in the evening is dependent on watching Coronation Street, say no.

124
00:19:38,867 --> 00:19:44,076
It can be very upsetting if the TV isn't working.

125
00:19:45,698 --> 00:19:48,382
I then get quite excited.

126
00:19:48,422 --> 00:19:52,928
I have to phone friends and ask to put it on a DVD and stuff like that.

127
00:19:57,714 --> 00:20:02,221
So the idea of enunciation is to find out where the attachments are.

128
00:20:02,721 --> 00:20:07,930
You don't have to go the whole hog, sort of drop everything and live under a tree.

129
00:20:08,752 --> 00:20:34,390
But you can do it in simple ways, you can find out where you're getting stuck, where you're holding on to something, where you find yourself getting upset over what is logically a rather silly thing, and you can begin to, as it were, withdraw your indulgence in that, see, and just feel the pain, the pain of letting go, see.

130
00:20:34,842 --> 00:21:00,511
and that pain of letting go isn't something which is bad it's something which is good because it's releasing us from that attachment that process of experiencing the pain of release is kernel to spiritual growth you see because

131
00:21:01,623 --> 00:21:03,884
What is it that we're releasing?

132
00:21:04,486 --> 00:21:08,569
We're releasing that, not simply that attachment to an object.

133
00:21:09,369 --> 00:21:14,816
That would be just very, shall we say, too restricted.

134
00:21:15,236 --> 00:21:20,300
We're actually releasing ourselves from a wrong view, a wrong understanding.

135
00:21:20,681 --> 00:21:27,968
That whatever happiness is to be found, it can't be found in an ephemeral, transient, unpredictable world.

136
00:21:31,963 --> 00:22:00,434
so by letting go of things as best we can we're actually repositioning ourselves in the world finding a different relationship with it and it's beginning to discover that which has the effect on us of developing a sense of calmness with it of developing a sense of patience just bearing with things without irritation not seeing that as a suffering

137
00:22:07,434 --> 00:22:21,376
now that's really one of the main things that we're learning when we sit in this meditation posture finding that observation post within us we've already discovered a transcendent position

138
00:22:23,534 --> 00:22:51,667
what we mean here by transcendent is that it is no longer involved or drawn into any confusion with any identity with any possession of whatever is being experienced so at a very simple level if I'm sitting here and pain comes to my knee in normal daily life I'd say my knee is hurting and I would try and do something about it

139
00:22:52,711 --> 00:23:00,221
But here, see, this is an opportunity to release myself from this relationship of my knee.

140
00:23:00,280 --> 00:23:11,776
If you were walking along the road and your leg fell off, see, you'd look at that leg, wouldn't you, and you'd say, well, is that my leg?

141
00:23:13,317 --> 00:23:16,402
See, it was my leg, but now it's on the road.

142
00:23:17,061 --> 00:23:18,203
How can I say it's my leg?

143
00:23:18,423 --> 00:23:19,865
That's a fiction, isn't it?

144
00:23:21,482 --> 00:23:22,944
If somebody says, whose leg is that?

145
00:23:23,484 --> 00:23:24,145
That's my leg.

146
00:23:25,928 --> 00:23:26,348
That's my leg.

147
00:23:26,509 --> 00:23:28,290
It's just fallen off.

148
00:23:29,291 --> 00:23:35,459
Now because you've reached this perfect equanimity, you would simply note that your leg had fallen off.

149
00:23:38,182 --> 00:23:43,808
And then you would hop merrily into Costa's for a coffee.

150
00:23:44,710 --> 00:23:47,153
It would be of little concern.

151
00:23:51,267 --> 00:23:53,069
But that's not what would happen really, would it?

152
00:23:53,570 --> 00:24:00,865
I mean, one would be in a state of shock.

153
00:24:00,884 --> 00:24:04,771
And that's really the problem with this identity.

154
00:24:05,313 --> 00:24:10,281
If it's me, if it's me we're talking about, then I lose a piece of me.

155
00:24:12,066 --> 00:24:12,886
That goes deep.

156
00:24:14,335 --> 00:24:43,869
that's why anything which happens to the body we might be glib about it we might say oh you know it's only the body and all that but when something serious moves in the body then you come across this huge fear this shock and that's the measure of our delusion about who we are but it doesn't take that much reflection to realise that we can't be the body even on a simple level of you know like

157
00:24:46,803 --> 00:24:50,125
well have you any idea what's going on in your liver at the moment?

158
00:24:53,288 --> 00:24:53,930
do you know where it is?

159
00:24:53,970 --> 00:25:00,336
do you experience your toenails growing?

160
00:25:01,377 --> 00:25:03,138
do you lose a part of yourself when you cut them off?

161
00:25:04,641 --> 00:25:16,792
see so just reflecting on the body as body as an actual you know just a physical piece of mechanism an organism

162
00:25:17,718 --> 00:25:21,580
you begin to realize, actually, you don't know it.

163
00:25:24,864 --> 00:25:27,026
We can't even see our own faces, for heaven's sake.

164
00:25:31,871 --> 00:25:35,073
When you look in the mirror, you think everybody sees you that way.

165
00:25:37,394 --> 00:25:39,297
But actually, have you done the double mirror thing?

166
00:25:40,218 --> 00:25:40,919
It comes as a shock.

167
00:25:41,219 --> 00:25:44,741
You never thought your ear was that big.

168
00:25:44,761 --> 00:25:46,002
Have you done that?

169
00:25:47,688 --> 00:25:55,163
Get two mirrors and look into the one that's looking into the mirror, that's catching your face.

170
00:25:55,184 --> 00:25:57,128
And that's how people see you.

171
00:25:57,148 --> 00:25:58,151
It's always the other way around.

172
00:26:04,244 --> 00:26:05,847
Don't get too depressed when you see it.

173
00:26:09,051 --> 00:26:13,704
Even when you see yourself in the mirror, even in that way, it's only a representation.

174
00:26:14,988 --> 00:26:18,116
We can't see our own face as we can see other people's faces.

175
00:26:24,626 --> 00:26:32,519
So this definition of who I am, you see, then you draw yourself into yourself with emotional states.

176
00:26:33,621 --> 00:26:37,426
And we find that there's not much control over that either.

177
00:26:37,988 --> 00:26:40,632
These emotions arise and pass away themselves.

178
00:26:41,353 --> 00:26:48,103
And they're often attached to certain things like meeting people and Coronation Street and things like that.

179
00:26:50,834 --> 00:26:56,682
To say to myself now, at this moment, you know, I will be happy, see, to command happiness.

180
00:26:59,806 --> 00:27:00,386
Can't do it again.

181
00:27:02,009 --> 00:27:07,856
You can pretend, you can jump up and down and sort of be happy, but the heart won't respond on a command.

182
00:27:11,642 --> 00:27:14,766
You don't go to bed thinking, well, tomorrow I'll wake up depressed.

183
00:27:17,159 --> 00:27:20,103
You go to bed with the expectation that you wake up refreshed, but you're not.

184
00:27:20,624 --> 00:27:21,585
Sometimes you're depressed.

185
00:27:23,667 --> 00:27:24,148
Thoughts.

186
00:27:26,451 --> 00:27:34,423
There we seem to have some sort of ability to guide our thoughts, to put our thoughts in a particular way and guide them, as it were.

187
00:27:36,205 --> 00:27:38,308
But often it's the thoughts that overtake us.

188
00:27:38,849 --> 00:27:43,115
We find ourselves dominated, compulsive thinking.

189
00:27:43,635 --> 00:28:10,098
we can't escape the little boxes that we've that we've created for ourselves so what the meditation is trying to make us do is to form a different relationship with it and what we find to our joy is that actually we don't have to do anything we don't have to change anything of the conditioning that we have and this is quite a relief

190
00:28:10,365 --> 00:28:36,576
you don't have to do anything about our depressions and our guilts and our feelings of embarrassments and all that you don't have to do anything about it all we have to do in that sense is this passive ability this ability to stay with what's arising and give them the time give them just that time and that inner space to express themselves

191
00:28:38,075 --> 00:29:06,798
and we find that when you just watch it like that it evaporates it begins to sort of expend its energy and in so doing it'll eventually draw those things to an end because it's only when they creep up into this thinking mind into the imagining mind that they develop themselves it's only through thought that an emotion develops itself

192
00:29:08,517 --> 00:29:14,384
And that's a real important insight to make into our psyche.

193
00:29:14,924 --> 00:29:20,230
That if you stop thinking depressing thoughts, the depression cannot develop.

194
00:29:21,152 --> 00:29:36,549
On the other hand, if you don't feel the depression, then the depression stays in the body as a turbulence, as an energy which isn't doing us any good, creating discomfort, illness, headaches, and all that sort of stuff.

195
00:29:38,520 --> 00:29:58,571
so it's not as though we can get rid of these conditionings on a word but we now know that we don't want to indulge them through thought and so we're left with just this situation of sitting with them and allowing them to express themselves

196
00:29:59,242 --> 00:30:26,904
now when you contact an emotional state say anger you feel irritated about something and you've cut off this avenue of constantly going over what it was that upset you and you come into the body and you feel the anger within your body and you're still saying to yourself this is anger this is anger not I am angry see you've separated this is anger

197
00:30:26,884 --> 00:30:38,163
As you, as it were, drop into that emotional state, so you're getting intimate with it, you want to find out what constitutes the emotion of anger.

198
00:30:38,984 --> 00:30:46,738
As you go into it, you may be surprised to find that all there is, is heat and movement.

199
00:30:47,640 --> 00:30:49,061
There's nothing there.

200
00:30:49,311 --> 00:30:55,624
The only thing that made it substantial was your positioning of saying I am angry.

201
00:30:55,983 --> 00:31:02,435
As soon as you say I, me, it becomes solid, it becomes something.

202
00:31:03,438 --> 00:31:12,213
Whereas when you experience it as just an emotional state, as just a sensation state, you find there's absolutely nothing there.

203
00:31:15,298 --> 00:31:21,744
And eventually that little flowering of anger begins to just fade away, it fades out.

204
00:31:22,685 --> 00:31:32,394
Now it's not as though that's the end of it, because there are these deeper dispositions which, you know, take their own time to purify.

205
00:31:36,278 --> 00:31:45,306
And that purification of the heart, shall we say, goes on automatically as soon as you're in this position of observing.

206
00:31:45,640 --> 00:31:51,853
or feeling of experiencing that's automatic you don't have to work at it you don't have to do anything

207
00:31:54,044 --> 00:32:04,717
And to maintain that objectivity, to maintain that position where you're not going to identify with this stuff, you're not concerned with the therapy of it.

208
00:32:05,117 --> 00:32:07,901
As soon as you do that, you become your own therapist.

209
00:32:08,461 --> 00:32:09,864
And that's always a danger, isn't it?

210
00:32:09,943 --> 00:32:13,868
Because it's the deluded trying to fix the deluded.

211
00:32:15,190 --> 00:32:17,452
So abandon that as absolutely hopeless.

212
00:32:19,458 --> 00:32:22,483
Instead, you see, the Buddha says, don't worry about that.

213
00:32:22,544 --> 00:32:27,032
Just let that burn itself out.

214
00:32:27,212 --> 00:32:28,596
We don't have to worry about that.

215
00:32:28,957 --> 00:32:30,179
That'll happen naturally.

216
00:32:30,779 --> 00:32:34,227
What we need to do is to correct our relationship to it.

217
00:32:35,641 --> 00:33:01,445
and he points to these three positions, so the first one is this impermanence so we begin to see that this solid thing that we used to call depression, anxiety and all that is actually nothing but just an amorphous blob of sensations there's actually nothing there, there's no substance to it

218
00:33:02,236 --> 00:33:32,057
and you begin to see that clearly when you experience it just as arising and passing away of sensations heat, pressure and so on and by doing that you come to the second understanding that if that's so then there's no substance to it it is insubstantial it has no entity of itself it's not an integer it doesn't have any being it doesn't have any existence

219
00:33:32,154 --> 00:33:33,577
It's just energy.

220
00:33:34,880 --> 00:33:41,132
And in fact, I tend to look upon my own emotional life as just weather patterns.

221
00:33:42,053 --> 00:33:43,154
I mean, what's a storm?

222
00:33:43,615 --> 00:33:50,930
It's just a couple of clouds coming over and a couple of bangs and flashes and then it moves on.

223
00:33:51,912 --> 00:33:55,377
It just blows itself out.

224
00:33:57,940 --> 00:34:08,398
And the third thing is this position that we have caused by that wrong relationship of wanting and not wanting, wanting and not wanting.

225
00:34:10,583 --> 00:34:22,563
So we're trying to access this transcendent point, we're at the apex of a triangle and we're looking down upon what is happening as it were beneath us.

226
00:34:23,422 --> 00:34:48,264
and on one side we're getting all those things that we've defined as pleasurable and on the other side as unpleasurable, just a longer continuum and that's your baseline, that's the given of human life you can't not be alive and not know that things are pleasant or unpleasant that's never the problem, things are always going to be pleasant or unpleasant

227
00:34:48,380 --> 00:34:59,583
Then you get this line that runs parallel to it, which is our reaction to it, which is wanting what is pleasant, not wanting what is unpleasant.

228
00:34:59,603 --> 00:35:03,411
And that reaction to it is causing the conflict.

229
00:35:03,431 --> 00:35:08,481
And when that reaction passes, there is only the pleasant and the unpleasant.

230
00:35:10,317 --> 00:35:36,914
and having abstracted ourselves, having uprooted ourselves from an identity with the pleasant and unpleasant we find ourselves in this transcendent position you see where there is just experience so the Buddha when he died of a stomach disease even right towards the end you see

231
00:35:37,418 --> 00:35:39,420
He's asking, are there any more questions?

232
00:35:39,539 --> 00:35:41,021
I mean, the man's dying.

233
00:35:41,121 --> 00:35:45,005
He's got gastroenteritis.

234
00:35:45,025 --> 00:35:46,527
And he's lying there and he knows he's dying.

235
00:35:46,867 --> 00:35:49,751
He knows he's dying and he says, is there any more questions before I go?

236
00:35:51,833 --> 00:35:55,458
And then just before he goes, he gives that salutary command.

237
00:35:55,478 --> 00:35:58,201
He says, all compounded things are transient.

238
00:35:58,221 --> 00:36:01,443
You know, work diligently for your liberation.

239
00:36:04,086 --> 00:36:04,688
And then he dies.

240
00:36:05,228 --> 00:36:05,568
Peacefully.

241
00:36:08,570 --> 00:36:09,871
what will be our last words?

242
00:36:11,293 --> 00:36:11,773
why me?

243
00:36:14,135 --> 00:36:14,735
why not you?

244
00:36:20,181 --> 00:36:36,456
just the arising and passing away of the human body and then when he died there were those younger monks around who weren't so trained and they began to cry and the elderly monks and the monks who were more advanced said what are you crying for?

245
00:36:36,637 --> 00:36:37,597
didn't you know that?

246
00:36:38,353 --> 00:37:00,396
everything arises and passes away and their attachment to the Buddha you see was based upon that wrong view so that's all we're doing in a sense through our meditation is discovering a new relationship with the world

247
00:37:03,329 --> 00:37:25,320
and the core practice of just being able to turn inward and to this introspection just to be able to observe ourselves you see so this intelligence that we have this intuitive intelligence it just begins to understand and that understanding then begins to change our attitudes

248
00:37:25,452 --> 00:37:33,367
And that attitude then begins to express itself in the way we speak, what we do, how we act, and through our livelihoods.

249
00:37:34,628 --> 00:37:36,291
And that's how this thing flows.

250
00:37:36,592 --> 00:37:41,402
It's a systemic effect on our lives.

251
00:37:45,753 --> 00:37:52,782
So that's what you might say the more passive side of the practice.

252
00:37:52,842 --> 00:37:59,793
The active side is what we'll come to this afternoon, which is of course developing the beautiful mind.

253
00:38:01,054 --> 00:38:08,385
Developing love, compassion, joy, peacefulness, and then through that to move into the world.

254
00:38:31,788 --> 00:38:45,056
So just to recap that, when we're sitting and the mind is wandering, the mind is thinking, unwittingly we're developing the old conditioning, we're making things worse.

255
00:38:45,717 --> 00:38:51,449
So we've got to be really right there with it as soon as we wake up and we have to acknowledge what the mind is doing.

256
00:38:52,088 --> 00:38:55,976
If the mind's worrying, we're not worried about content, right?

257
00:38:55,996 --> 00:39:00,286
Just don't give an ounce of interest to content.

258
00:39:01,007 --> 00:39:02,992
Just worry about it.

259
00:39:03,800 --> 00:39:33,012
worry about the attitude so if you see that you're worrying about something so worry when you come into the body you see see if you can feel the worry as an emotional state within the body and if you can't find you go back to the breath and if you can find it if it's there quite obvious to you then stay with it wait for it to die out and you'll see the thoughts die out and then that connection between thought and emotion becomes more apparent to us

260
00:39:33,262 --> 00:39:41,054
If you're sitting there and you feel a disturbance in the body, a tension in the stomach, something like that, you see, don't guess.

261
00:39:41,715 --> 00:39:48,065
Don't say to yourself, this is anxiety, or this is worry, or this is grief or something, see?

262
00:39:48,505 --> 00:39:50,427
Just feel it as feeling.

263
00:39:51,369 --> 00:40:15,284
that feeling which may very well be an emotional state caught up in that part of the body may rise to the point in the heart, into the heart center where you can recognize it as an emotion or it may dissipate itself through the body so that when that tension goes that particular mental state has also been exhausted

264
00:40:15,652 --> 00:40:28,802
this is also true of illnesses that are caused by the mind psychosomatic illnesses not all illnesses are caused by that of course

265
00:40:30,875 --> 00:40:39,322
And the only other thing that I'll mention just towards the end is the other side, which is this disappearing into sleep.

266
00:40:40,784 --> 00:40:45,949
So remember, the mind needs rest, sure, the body needs rest.

267
00:40:46,811 --> 00:40:58,501
But if you've had a good night's sleep and you feel generally rested, then in your meditation, if this dullness comes and this feeling of lethargy, don't fool yourself, don't say, well, I must be tired.

268
00:40:59,646 --> 00:41:01,751
Because this is sloth and torpor.

269
00:41:02,632 --> 00:41:07,762
And the instruction there is to remain awake at all costs.

270
00:41:09,164 --> 00:41:14,333
So whether you open your eyes or stand up or if it gets really bad, do some walking meditation.

271
00:41:14,713 --> 00:41:21,485
But be absolutely steadfast in your commitment and refuse to be annihilated.

272
00:41:23,557 --> 00:41:29,128
And when you do the walking meditation or your standing, you see, don't try and get rid of it.

273
00:41:29,547 --> 00:41:31,210
See, this is the thing that we tend to do.

274
00:41:31,231 --> 00:41:35,077
You feel a bit, you know, lazy until you're going jumping up and down, you see.

275
00:41:35,699 --> 00:41:42,090
But actually all you're doing is suppressing that conditioning which is drawing us into oblivion.

276
00:41:42,070 --> 00:41:45,780
So when you feel the heaviness and the dullness, stay with it.

277
00:41:45,800 --> 00:41:47,204
Make that your object, you see.

278
00:41:47,545 --> 00:41:49,831
Allow that energy to dissipate itself.

279
00:41:50,251 --> 00:41:53,480
We don't see it as energy because it's drawing us down into something.

280
00:41:53,961 --> 00:41:55,184
But it's like black holes.

281
00:41:55,672 --> 00:41:57,715
You get drawn into the inner black hole.

282
00:41:58,237 --> 00:42:03,425
So it's a real energy, it's a force that wants us to move towards oblivion.

283
00:42:04,407 --> 00:42:12,021
And we teach ourselves that every time the alarm goes and you turn over and wait for the snooze button.

284
00:42:12,862 --> 00:42:19,434
Every time you do that, there's another little weight just drawing us down into oblivion.

285
00:42:20,494 --> 00:42:25,186
And of course the attraction of oblivion is that there is no suffering.

286
00:42:25,467 --> 00:42:27,492
There's no suffering in oblivion.

287
00:42:28,554 --> 00:42:28,956
Wonderful.

288
00:42:29,717 --> 00:42:31,242
But unfortunately we keep waking up.

289
00:42:32,405 --> 00:42:35,532
So that's our problem.

290
00:42:36,610 --> 00:42:50,592
So when we come across this other side, the bit that is lacking energy, when we feel that sort of heaviness and the dullness of the mind, you know, we're doing this sort of stuff, just open your eyes, stand up, stretch yourself, you know.

291
00:42:50,652 --> 00:42:52,315
But you're not trying to get rid of it.

292
00:42:53,137 --> 00:42:56,963
Don't get into a battle with these conditionings.

293
00:42:57,423 --> 00:43:00,829
Just give them the space and time to just burn themselves out.

294
00:43:06,681 --> 00:43:09,494
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

295
00:43:10,398 --> 00:43:16,202
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.
